{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92060454/00393346759/1945110301/0188.xml":{"full_text":"_____ Hertford conn\nA Hinton Ctrnesi\n__ II Official Weekly Labor Organ Voicing The Interests Of The American Federation of Labor\nVOT 5 Wo, 78 Eatered as Second Clue Matter May S, 1941, at the Poet Office\nv ANO* Haven. Conn., under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNEW HAVEN, CONN., SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 1945\nA.F.L. NEWS SERVICE PRICE 5 CENTS\nU.S. Ends Building Trades Wage Controls\nLabor In Conn.\n'Disappointed\u2019 In\nTruman Speech\nFeinmark Says Industry\u2019s\nProfits Permit Wage Rise\nWithout Price Rise\nDisappointment that Presi\ndent Truman was not more\nspecific in his radio address\non wages and hours Tuesday\nnight was expressed by Secre\ntary-Treasurer Harold V.\nFeinmark of the Connecticut\nFederation of Labor.\nAlthough praising the Presi\ndent for his understanding of\nthe situation in which labor now\nfinds itself, with take-home pay\ngreatly reduced, Feinmark said\nthat organized labor desires to\nreturn to the process of real col\nlective bargaining, and is opposed\nto the return of the War Labor\nBoard, or any other government\nagency, which will have the\npower to establish wage rates.\nIn his statement, Feinmark\nalso said:\n\u201cWe are disappointed that Pres\nident Truman was not more speci\nfic in his discussion of the wage\nand hour problems of American\nworking people.\n\u201cHowever, the President has recog\nnized two facts which bear out the\ncontentions of organized labor. One is\nthat working people and their families\ncannot maintain a decent standard of\nliving on the old 40-hour rate.\nSecondly, in most cases, industry can\nraise wage rates and make a reason\nable profit without increasing prices.\nGREAT PROFITS\n\u201cSince V-J Day, we have insisted\nthat the great profits made by man\nagement during the war, aided by\ncorporation-slanted tax laws, and\nI labor\u2019s greatly increased productivity,\nmake it possible for employers to pay\nwages which will maintain purchas\ning power and at the same time en\nable workers to avoid sub-standard\nliving conditions.\n\u201cWe congratulate President\nTruman for his. insistence that a\nreal Unemployment Compensation\nLaw be passed, and on his support\nof the Full Employment Bill. It is\nhigh time that Congress stopped\ngassing, and passed these bills,\nwhich are basic to the reconversion\nprogram.\nBricklayers Of\nState Condemn\n'Ball-Chain\u2019 Act\n_\nAnnual State Session Hears\nAddresses By Feinmark\nAnd O\u2019Toole\nThe Connecticut State Confer\nence of Bricklayers, Masons, and\nPlasterers held their annual meet\ning at the New Haven Labor Tem\nple Saturday, heard two of their\ninternational vice-presidents report\non the current situation, elected\nofficers; and passed a number of\nimportant resolutions. The speak\ners included Harold V. Feinmark\nand J. Lawrence O\u2019Toole, secre\ntary-treasurer and assistant secre\ntary, respectively, of the Connecti\ncut Federation of Labor, who ex\nplained the changes made by the\nLegislature in the unemployment\n1 compensation and workmen\u2019s com\npensation acts.\n(Continued on Page Four)\nRourke To Tangle\nWith Miss Kellems\nJoseph M. Rourke, business man\nager of No. B-90, Electricians Union,\nwill make his first public appearance\nsince returning to civilian life, over\nStation WICC, Bridgeport and New\nHaven, on Friday, Nov. 2, at 9:30 P.M.\nAt that time he will participate in a\nradio forum entitled \u201cCan We Have\nWage Increases Without Having\nPrice Increases?\u201d Together with an\nother representative of labor, he will\nbe opposed by two members of man\nagement, one of whom will be Miss\nVivien Kellems, the very-well-known\nWestport industrialist.\nBuilding Trades Obtain Minimum Rate From State Wage Board\nJAMES O\u2019KANE\nSecretary Treasurer, Conn.\nBuilding Trades Council.\nWILLIAM F. FARGO\nB.A., Carpenters, No. 30,\nNew London.\nJOHN A. JOHNSON\nB.A., Carpenters, No. 79,\nNew Haven.\nTHOMAS YOCZIK\nPresident, State Council of Car\npenters\nMeeting in New Haven with the State Wage Board, the above, representatives of the Connecticut State Building and Con\nstruction Trades Council, were successful this week in establishng a minimum rate of $1.50 per hour on all highway and bridge\nwork done for the state of Connecticut. This rate is strictly a minimum one, O\u2019Kane points out, and does not apply where there is\nan agreement which contains a higher rate. This is the first time a minimum rate of this kind has been obtained from the State\nWage Board, and is due to the activities of the Conn. Building Trades Council.\n\u201cNo Soap\u201d Says\nRockbestos To\nUnion Demands\nElectrical Workers To Seek\nConciliator Before Tak\ning Strike Vote\nBy \u201cLee\u201d Vigneault, Bus. Mgr.\nLocal N.B. 1370, I.B.E.W.\n\u201cWhat did Rockbestos offer?\u201d This\nquestion was eagerly put to the nego\ntiating committee by local officers and\nstewards as they met Sunday at the\nNew Haven Labor Temple for a re\nport on the following demands of\nLocal 1370:\n1. A 30% wage increase to off\nset an announced 40-hour work\nweek.\n2. Straight time pay for holi\ndays not worked.\n3. Six days cumulative sick\nleave pay per year.\n4. Three weeks vacation for all\nemployees with 15 years seniority\nor more. (It is now 1 week for one\nyear; two weeks for 5 years and\nover.)\n5. Pro-rated vacation pay for\nemployees laid-off because of lack\nof work.\n6. A modified closed shop.\nThe answer left a dark brown\ntaste! The negotiating committee re\nported that the Company will not\nagree to negotiate the above demands\non the ground that they have noth\ning to do with Executive Order No.\n9240.\nA CALM APPROACH!\n\u201cOur members will boil when they\nhear this! We won\u2019t be able to stop\nthem from walking out!\u201d In spite of\nstatements such as these, the Officers\nand Stewards pledged to support a\nmove by the Local Union to ad\nvise its membership not to resort to\nwalkouts until all means of collective\nbargaining had been exhausted.\n\u201cThat\u2019s throwing fuel on the fire!\u201d\nshouted one of the Stewards when\nthey were told that the Company\n(Continued on Page Two'.\nMurphy Endorsed\nBy Cigar Makers\nCigar Makers Union 39, at its\nregular weekly meeting Monday\nunanimously endorsed John W.\nMurphy for reelection as mayor of\nthe City of New Haven for the eighth\nconsecutive term. The union issued\nthe following statement:\n\u201cMayor Murphy is now and has\nbeen since boyhood, a member in good\nstanding, of Cigar Makers Union 39.\nBefore his election as mayor of New\nHaven, Mr. Murphy was always ac\ntive in the affairs of his union, for\nmany years as recording secretary\nbusiness agent, always assisting the\nmembers in getting better working\nconditions and more pay.\n\u201cWe are proud of Brother Mur\nphy\u2019s record as a member of Cigar\nMakers Union, and just as proud of\nhis record as mayor of New Haven\nfor the past 14 years.\u201d\nAs We See It\nby\nTHE STAFF\nCONGRESS is contemplating a\nlaw banning strikes. If the baby\ncries, cut his head off. That\u2019ll keep\nhim quiet.\n\nJIMMY McCarthy, business\nagent of the Waterbury Bricklay\ners and Building Laborers, went to\nthe Waterbury Hospital Wednesday\nfor a major operation. He will be\nout of the hospital in about ten\ndays.\n\nTHANKS to an alert proofread\ner, this copy for a classified ad in\nthe Leavenworth (Kan.) Times did\nnot run \u201cas is\u201d under the Miscel\nlaneous heading:\nLIGHT HAULING and 24-hour\nwench service. Phone\n\nMany unions are continuing to\nwin substantial wage increases ovei\nthe conference table without\nstrikes, the A. F. of L. revealed this\nweek.\n\u201cUnions affiliated with the Fed\neration report wage increases dur\ning the last month of from 5 to 15\ncents an hour, or even 20 cents,\naffecting hundreds of thousands of\nmembers,\u201d the Federation de\nclared.\n\u201cOne of our largest internation\nals discloses that in 98 per cent of\nits local wage negotiations increases\nare being secured without threat\n(Continued on Page Two)\ni-\u2014\nAnnual Meeting,\nSplendidBanquet\nHeld By Barbers\nLieut. Gov. Snow, Mayor\nCubeta, And Feinmark\nAmong Speakers\nWith a maximum attendance of\n225 members, the 44th annual con\nvention of the Connecticut Journey\nmen Barbers\u2019 Protective Association,\nheld this week-end at the Hotel\nGarde, was one of the most successful\nin the history of the organization.\nBoth* the business sessions, and the\nbanquet, were among the best ever\nheld.\nThe banquet was one of the high\nlights of the two-day session.\nGiven in honor of Michael Patru\ncello of Local 648, Middletown,\nwho was named Deputy Barber\nCommissioner by Gov. Raymond E.\nBaldwin, speakers at the festivities\nincluded Lieut. Gov. Wilbert Snow\nof Conn.; Mayor Cubeta of Middle\ntown; Harold V. Feinmark, secre\ntary-treasurer of the Conn. Feder\nation of Labor; Anthony Merlino,\n3rd International Vice-President;\nand Albert Schiavone, examiner of\nthe State Barbers Board; and the\nbarber commissioners of the state.\nState President Joseph J. Summa\nof Waterbury, No. 732, was toast\nmaster. Sam Labella of No. 648 pre\n(Continued on Page Five)\nCalifornia Machinists\nWant Bilbo Impeached\nSAN DIEGO, Calif.\u2014(FP)\u2014Im\npeachment of Sen. Theodore Bilbo\n(I), Miss.) is demanded in a petition\ncirculated here by Lodge 1125, Inti.\nAssn, of Machinists (OAFL). The\npolltaxer is denounced for \u201ccarrying\non fascists tirades against minority\ngroups and ranting on about such re\nvolting terms as nigger, dago and\nkike.\u201d\nHenry Geis New\nHead Of State\nElectricians\nHanley, Miller, And Morris\nAlso Named\u2014Tribute\nTo McCurry\nHenry Geis, of Local B-90, New\nHaven, was elected president of the\nConnecticut State Association of\nElectrical Workers, at the annual\nmeeting of the Association, held\nSaturday at the New Haven Labor\nTemple. Tom Hanley, of Stamford,\nwas named vice-president; Alex\nMiller of New Britain, secretary;\nand Joseph Morris, B-1013, Hart\nford, and a vice-president of the\nConnecticut Federation of Labor,\nwas elected treasurer. The officers\nwere installed by former president\n(Continued on Page Two)\nConn. Farmer-Labor Unity Urged\nThe Connecticut Farm Bu\nreau Federation, meeting at\nthe Hotel Bond Tuesday, re\nceived a recommendation that\norganized labor and the farm\ners of this state establish \u201ca\ncloser relationship.\u201d\nThe recommendation was\nmade by Harold V. Feinmark,\nsecretary-treasurer of the Con\nnecticut Federation of Labor,\nwho told the Farm Bureau Fed\neration that \u201cwe have many\nproblems which are mutual to\nboth groups, and which cannot be\nsolved unless we understand\neach other, and work together.\u201d\nFeinmark is believed to he\nthe first representative of or\nganized labor asked to address\nthe farmers\u2019 organization. He\nsaid, in part:\nAGREE ON ISSUES\n\u201cOne of the first plans I made\nwhen I was elected secretary-treas\nurer of the Connecticut Federation\nof I^ahor was to find out if it was\npossible to establish a closer re\nlationship between the working\npeople and the farmers of our\nstate. That is why, when I say\nthat I am glad to he here, I am\nnot making a routine opening\nstatement. I am convinced, as I\nhope you arc, that we have many\nproblems which are mutual to both\nN. H. Labor Institute\nTo Open Wednesday\nThe Diocesan Labor Institute, New\nHaven Chapter, will begin its fall\nsessions on Wednesday evening, No\nvember 7th, in the studios of Station\nVVNHC, 1110 Chapel Street at 8\nclock. There will be courses in labor\n-thics, labor history, and parliamen\ntary procedure. The social teachings\n)f the Church will be stressed. This\ninaugurates a three-year course.\nQuestions from the audience will\nbe freely discussed. There is no charge\naf any kind and the public is invited.\ngroups, and which cannot he solved\nunless we understand each other,\nand work together.\u201d\n\u201cLet me point out at the very out- 1\nset some of the issues on which, I\nbelieve, we are in complete agree\nment. Working farm people\u2019s post\nwar hopes and fears\u2014are very much\nthe same as labor\u2019s hopes and fears.\nbanners hope for a just and last\ning peace among the nations and\nwithin the United States. So does\nlabor, of course, banners hope for\nfull production and employment. So\ndoes labor. Last year, all three farm\norganizations at their conventions,\nwent on record in favor of world\norganization to make and keep tin\npeace. So did organized labor.\n\u201cBoth farmers and labor fear a\nleturn to chronic mass unemployment\nafter this war. To farmers, unem\nployment means shrinking markets\nand prices for farm products. To\nlabor it means a reduced standard of\nliving, ill health, and all of the mis\nery that goes with unemployment. To\nfarmers, chronic mass unemployment\nfurther means that millions will be\ndriven off their own land to work the\nland of others for low and uncertain\nwages, and to go to the cities to com\npete with city wage-earners for few\ner and fewer jobs at lower and low\ner wages.\nFAMINE PLENTY\n\u201cI know that I am telling you\nnothing new when I point out that\nshrinkage of industrial production,\nemployment, wages and purchas\ning power creates! so-called sur\npluses\u2019 of farm products. In the\nlast depression, farmers burned\n10-cent corn and 3\u00a9-cent wheat\nwhile miners and factory workers\nand their families went hungry.\nNeither could buy the other\u2019s prod\nucts.\n\u201cLabor has the problem of monopo\nlies and cartels limiting production,\nthus reducing employment opportu\nnities. Farmers have a similar prob\nlem\u2014the difference between family\ntype farms and the big commercial\nized and industrialized farms. The\nsmall farmer finds it difficult to com\npete with the industrialized farm,\nwhich we call \u2018factories in the field.\u2019\n\u201cThe small farmers cannot and\nwill not sweat themselves and their\nfamilies, their own flesh and blood,\n(Continued on Page Four)\nWages Can Go Up\nBy At Least 24%\nIndustry Would Still Make Profits Of $6,300,000,000\nAfter Taxes, Government Economists Reveal\u2014Or\nganized Labor\u2019s Stand On Rates Fully Supported\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Labor\u2019s j\nwage demands received a consider-\nable boost here last week, with the\nrevelation by a group of conomists\ndealing directly with the White\nHouse that industry as a whole\ncould pay a 24% wage increase\nand still make stupendous profits\nof $6,300,000,000 after taxes in\n1946.\nThe figures were part of a report\nprepared by the economists in the Of\nfice of War Mobilization and Recoil-\nversion for the OWMR\u2019s Advisory\nBoard, which met last week to discuss\nAdministration wage policies. The\nBoard advises Reconversion Director\nJohn W. Snyder, and includes lead\ners of labor, industry, farm and civic\ngroups appointed by the President.\nLEAKED TO PRESS\nWhile unions assert that a 30%\nbasic pay increase is possible while\nindustry can still make high prof\nits, labor economists here were\nquick to assert that the White\nHouse report, which \u201cleaked\u201d to\nthe press, substantially reinforced\ntheir own very detailed calculations\non which wage negotiations in\nmany industries are now proceed\ning.\nHere are some of the conclusions\nof the White House economists:\nThe take-home pay of the average\nindustrial worker in 1946 will have\n10% less purchasing power, after he\npays his taxes, than did his earnings\nin January of 1941. His weekly pay\ncheck will be down 28% within a\nfew months from wartime levels.\nCOSTS TO DECLINE\nDeclines in costs, which can be ac\ncurately measured, will improve man\nagement's ability to pay wage raises,\nthough some other factors may impair\nthis ability.\nBased on these measurable de\nclines in costs, wage rate increases\naveraging 24% for all industry\ncould be granted due to the ending\nof overtime, downgrading, and the\nending of the excess profits tax.\nUnemployment will reach 8,000,\n000 by next spring, and national\noutput will decline about 25%\nfrom $206 billion to $165 billion\nor less.\n\u201cThe behavior of the stock market\nin recent months,\u201d according to\nOWMR economists, \u201csuggests that\nthe business and linancial community\nexpect profits after taxes to remain\nat or near wartime peak. The mar\nket value of securities on the N. Y.\nStock Exchange has risen by a third\nsince D day and by 10% between V-J\nDay and Sept. 30, 1945.\u201d\nTobin Ready To\nLock Horns With\nMilk Industry\nTeamsters Want Jobs For\n38,000 Members Coming\nOut Of Army\nCINCINNATI, O.\u2014(FP\u2014Pres.\nDaniel J. Tobin of the Inti. Bro. of\nTeamsters, attending the AFL exec\nutive council meeting here, said the\nunion was \u201cready to fco out\u201d if neces\nsary to enforce daily delivery of milk\nto homes after Nov. 1.\nA federal regulation providing\nfor everv-other-day delivery, put\ninto effect as a war measure in\n1942, expires on that date. Dis\ncussions here between Tobin and\nPaul Porter, spokesman for the\ndairy industry, revealed the indus\ntry\u2019s reluctance to resume daily de\nliveries.\nTobin charged the milk companies\nwere attempting to cut out deliveries\naltogether. About 38,000 union mem\nbers in the industry are being released\nfrom the armed forces, he said, and\nthe present delivery system will not\nmake it possible for milk firms to\ngive employment to all who worked\nin the industry under the daily-de\nlivery system.\nTYPOS GET PAY BOOST\nWASHINGTON LPA)\u2014About\n500 printers, members of Columbia\nTypographical Union 101, will receive\na weekly pay raise of $6.10 from the\nfour daily newspapers here. The new\nrate is for a 35-hour, five-day week,\nand is scaled for shift differentials.\nTruman Names\nAFL Delegates\nTo Conference\nGreen, Meany, Bates, To\nbin And Hutcheson\nHead The List\nFollowing are the delegates and al\nternates named to represent the\nAmerican Federation of Labor at the\nLabor-Industry Conference called by\nPresident Truman to meet in Wash\nington Nov. Sth:\nWilliam Green, AFL President.\nGeorge Meany, AFL Secretary\nTreasurer.\nntirry u nates, ^resident, Brick\nlayers, Masons Plasterers.\nDaniel J. Tobin, President, In\nternational Brotherhood of Team\nsters.\nWilliam L. Hutcheson, Presi\ndent, United Brotherhood of Car\npenters.\nDavid Dubinsky, President, In\nternational Ladies\u2019 Garment Work\ners.\nGeorge Harrison, President,\nBrotherhood, of Railway Clerks.\nMatthew Woll, Vice-President,\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nCharles J. MacGowan, President,\nInternational Brotherhood of Boil\nermakers.\nA. L. Spradling, Assistant Presi\ndent, Amalgamated Association of\nStreet Electric Railway Em\nployes.\nMartin Durkin, President, Unit\ned Association of Plumbers and\nSteam Fitters.\nHerman Winter, President, Bak\nery and Confectionery Workers.\nEd J. Brown, President, Interna\ntional Brotherhood of Electrical\nWorkers.\nPatrick E. Gorman, Secretary\nTreasurer, Amalgamated Meat\nCutters.\nJam^s M. Duffy, President,\nBrotherhood of Operative Potters.\nElmer E. Milliman, President,\nBrotherhood of Maintenance of\nWay Employes.\nPublic\u2019s Views Are\nAsked By Union\nPortland, Ore. (LPA)\u2014The Lum\nber Sawmill Workers, AFL, have\ntaken their claim for $1.10 an hour\nwork rate directly to the public. An\nid in the Vancouver (daily) Sun,\n[leaded \u201cA Labor Union\u2019s Report to\nthe Public on the Lumber Strike\u201d\nisks \u201cIs $1.10 an hour unreasonable?\u201d\nstates the factors involved, and pro\nvides a reply cdupon for tallying the\npublic's opinion.\n---1\nHonor For Conn.\nBRIEN McMAIION,\nII. S. Senator from Connecticut,\nhas achieved world fame by be\ning named chairman of the\nSenate's special committee on\nthe problems of atomic power.\nConn. Councils\nDrive Helped To\nAchieve Results\nState Board Pushes For\nPassage Of Wagner\nEllender Bill\nSuccess this week crowned\nseveral months of intense ac\ntivity by the Connecticut State\nBuilding and Construction\nTrades Council, together\nwith building trades councils\nthroughout the country, to\nbring an end to the Wage\nStabilization Agreement, atid\nto the Wage Adjustment\nBoard.\nA letter received by James\nO\u2019Kane, secretary-treasurer of\nthe State Building Trades Coun\ncil, from Herbert A. Rivers,\nsecretary of the A.F.L.\u2019s Build\ning and Construction Trades De\npartment, announces that these\nobjectives have been accom\nplished. The text of the letter\nfrom Rivers follows:\nENDS NOV. 18\n\u201cThe Executive Council had un\nder consideration the termination\ndate of the Stabilization Agreement\nwhich was entered into August 1,\n1941, at its October 10-13, 1945,\nmeeting and it was the decision of\nthe Executive Council that this\nagreement should be withdrawn as\nof November 18, 1945.\n\u201cThe question of overtime rates\nand other working conditions\nwhich were changed by the Stabil\nization Agreement will be a subject\nfor National and International un\nion and local unions to adjust with\ntheir employers.\n\u201cThe Wage Stabilization Agree\nment which was entered into May\n22, 1942, between the National\nand International Unions in affilia\ntion with this Department and the\nDepartment of Labor was also can\ncelled and withdrawn effective as\nof November 18, 1945. No cases\nwill be received by the Wage Ad\njustment Beard after October 27,\n1945.\u201d\nUiriUE TO OPEN\nThe State Building Trades Coun\ncil was hitting on. all cylinders this\nweek. Preparations for opening the\nState Office in New Haven are al\nmost completed, and plans will be an\nnounced at the meeting of the execu\ntive board, to be held in New Haven\nWednesday, Nov. 7 at 11 A.M. The\nmeeting with the State Wage Board\nwas highly successful, and the cam\npaign for all locals to order their\n\u201cVictory Campaign\u201d buttons is mak\ning progress. It is clear that the\nState Building Trades Council is one\nof the most active in the country, and\neven larger results could be obtained\nif more locals would pitch in and give\ntheir full support.\nHOUSING BILL\nPassage of the Wagner-Ellender\nHousing Bill (S. 1320), is one of\nthe outstanding objectives of the\nbuilding trades at this time, and\nConnecticut is doing its full share\nto insure victory in this campaign.\nThis bill sets up a comprehen\nsive national housing policy, and\nis intended to encourage a con\nstruction drive which wifi result in\nthe building of 1,500,000 new\nhomes each year for the next ten\nyears. In addition, it is the only\ntangible proposal now before Con\ngress for the creation of millions\nof new jobs.\nBARRY URGES jfCTION\nPresident Michael J. Barry of the\nState Council this week issued an\nurgent appeal to all locals and build\ning trades councils to write their\ncongressmen and senators urging\nthem to obtain immediate action on,\nand vote for the bill.\n(Continued on Page Four)\nN. H. Candidates To\nBroadcast Friday\nStation WELI is sponsoring a\nmayoralty candidates\u2019 meeting Friday\nevening, Nov. 2, at 8 o\u2019clock for the\nGreater New Haven League of Wom\nen Voters.\nMayor John W. Murphy, William\nC. Celentatio, and Alfred Tong will\nspeak on issues of the campaign fol\nlowed by questions from the audience.\nGeorge Bronson will act as Modera\ntor. This program has been planned\nas a public service so that the elec\ntorate may hear all of the candidates\nat one time.\nLet's Finish The Job\u2014Support The Victory Loan\u2014Buy Bonds","height":"26595","width":"20766"}}
